chronic neuropathic pain, which is often treated with medications that modulate neuronal excitability. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnticonvulsants\u003C/strong\u003E are effective in this context because they can suppress glutaminergic transmission and block calcium channels, thereby reducing neuronal excitability and pain perception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntidepressants\u003C/strong\u003E can also be used in neuropathic pain management, but they primarily work through modulation of serotonin and noradrenaline pathways rather than calcium channel blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioids\u003C/strong\u003E are potent analgesics but do not specifically target glutaminergic transmission or calcium channels. They work primarily through mu-opioid receptor agonism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECannabinoids\u003C/strong\u003E have been explored for pain management, but their mechanisms are distinct from those of anticonvulsants and involve cannabinoid receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntipyretic analgesics\u003C/strong\u003E like paracetamol are not effective for neuropathic pain as they do not target the specific pathways involved in this type of pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anticonvulsants can be used in pain management due to their ability to suppress glutaminergic transmission and block calcium channels.","These mechanisms help in reducing neuronal excitability and are effective in treating neuropathic pain."],"references":["Rho JM, White HS. Brief history of anti-seizure drug development. Epilepsia Open. 2018 Oct 24;3(Suppl Suppl 2):114-119. doi: 10.1002/epi4.12268. PMID: 30564769; PMCID: PMC6293064.","Angus-Leppan H, Sperling MR, Villanueva V. Antiseizure medications (antiepileptic drugs) in adults: starting, monitoring and stopping. J Neurol. 2023 Jan;270(1):573-581. doi: 10.1007/s00415-022-11378-3. Epub 2022 Sep 24. PMID: 36153467.","Stefan H, Feuerstein TJ. 